body:
There are:
a) static libraries (*.a)
b) shared libraries (*.so)

Static library is essentialy a set of object files.

How to create an object file?
tools.cpp

```c++
    #include <iostream>

    using namespace std;

    int foo()
    {
    cout << "I'm foo()" << endl;
    }
```
g++ -c tools.cpp
"the -c option says not to run the linker" (man page citation)
Result: tools.o (an object file)

How to create a static library?
ar -cq libtools.a tools.o

And check the results:
[root@norbert-redhat lib]# ar -t libtools.a
tools.o

So... how to use it?
main.cpp
#include <iostream>
#include "tools.h"

using namespace std;

int main()
{
        cout << "I'm calling foo()..." << endl;
        foo();
        cout << "I'm back!" << endl;
}


g++ -L . main.cpp -ltools



Możesz znaleźć biblioteki statyczne
find / -name *.a 2>/dev/null

Co jest w takim archiwum
ar -t toextract.a

Biblioteka statyczna to tak naprawdę pliki .o
pliki pośrednie?
